71, "end": 576}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "KIF1A", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8728305101394653, "span": {"begin": 593, "end": 598}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:547"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "KIF1A mutant", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8191350698471069, "span": {"begin": 593, "end": 605}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8698293566703796, "span": {"begin": 606, "end": 610}}, {"id": ["mim:145900", "mesh:D015417"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "motor and sensory disturbances", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999431371688843, "span": {"begin": 621, "end": 651}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "axons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5276693105697632, "span": {"begin": 726, "end": 731}}], "text": "Defects in axonal transport are often suggested as a cause for peripheral neuropathies as the length-dependent, distal neurologic deficits observed in patients treated with taxol or other MSAs indicate an axonal loss comparable to dying-back neuropathies which are often linked to axonal transport defects. [1]  Mutations linked to axonal transport are known to cause Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (peripheral neuropathy). A mutation in the gene coding for the motor protein kinesin 1B (KIF1B) was found in a CMT2A family. The transport of synaptic vesicles is mediated by KIF1B. [2]  Generated KIF1A mutant mice exhibited motor and sensory disturbances and transport of synaptic vesicle precursors was shown to be decreased in axons. [3]", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:14:58 +0000 2026"}